Our role as activists is to push open the Overton Window, to shift public perceptions in the direction of acceptance of what was once unimaginable. We lead a shift in the hearts and minds of the public by illustrating the urgency of animal liberation in these unprecedented times, and how all struggles for liberation are part of the same paradigm. 

This requires brave, bold and strategic messaging and action. Nothing changes when we obediently accept the justifications from those in power for why things must remain the same. Activism calls on us to question, disobey and sometimes move outside of our own comfort zone. Through activism we grow personally and immensely.

That's why ‚Äî to cite an example of one of our many 2021 campaigns ‚Äî we refused to be ignored by Illinois Department of Ag. officials and targeted Illinois Governor Pritzker, which led to the Illinois Attorney General granting our request to investigate the Director of Ag. for his failure to enforce laws on slaughterhouses. 

We know that strategic activism can bring about rapid and powerful results, so one of our primary goals is to bring out the activist spirit in everyone. Mentoring and training activists is in fact central to our mission. We meet each person where they are and help guide them on their journey.

Thank you so much for your support and commitment to helping animals!

Winter is hotpot weather, so my friend and I decided to branch out of our usual Chinatown spots to check out @haidilaohotpotus in South Loop! In China, Haidilao is synonymous with over-the-top service and flavorful broths so my expectations were quite high as I used to go to the ones in Shanghai all the time. We got the milky pork bone and tomato broth-- the latter especially was excellent. Also tried out some seafood items, veggies, and wagyu beef! Honestly I'm glad I went and got the chance to experience their fun little twists such as the robot servers and dancing noodles but I'll probably just stick to Chinatown next time (mostly because of AYCE deals and free sauce bars üòÖ).

RESTAURANT #30/365: BITES Asian Kitchen + Bar @biteschicago (3313 N Clark St, Chicago, IL 60657)

Well, I don't know if I'll make it to 10% of 365 by the end of the year, but I at least made it to number 30 with my visit to BITES Asian Kitchen + Bar!

I ordered their chicken katsudon and a duck bao. The bao was amazing: super juicy and full of flavor! The katsudon was really good too: with nori, ginger, egg, and a teriyaki sauce, the very filling bowl had the perfect mix of savory and slightly sweet flavor.

I was tempted to get a drink, but decided not to seeing as it wasn't even noon yet. I'll have to try one of their cocktails next time!
